<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Quercus</i> <i>sadleriana</i> is dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>nevadensis</i>, <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>patula</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>cordulatus</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>cuneatus</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>velutinus</i>, <i>Chrysolepis</i> <i>sempervirens</i>, <i>Holodiscus</i> <i>discolor</i>, <i>Prunus</i> <i>emarginata</i>, <i>Quercus</i> <i>vacciniifolia</i>, <i>Rhododendron</i> <i>macrophyllum</i>, <i>Symphoricarpos</i> <i>mollis</i> and <i>Vaccinium</i> <i>membranaceum</i>. Emergent conifers may be present at low cover, including <i>Pinus</i> <i>lambertiana</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>ponderosa</i> or <i>Pseudotsuga</i> <i>menziesii</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 3 m; canopy is intermittent to continuous. Herbaceous layer is sparse. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Quercus sadleriana</i> > 60% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Sawyer et al. 1978b).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
