<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Quercus sadleriana </i>is an evergreen shrub that grows to 3 m in height. Leaves are prominently pinnate-veined, regularly serrate, and mostly glabrous. Shrubs produce large acorn crops at irregular intervals. Seeds germinate without stratification. Small animals cache the acorns, which other wildlife eat also. Plants sprout from swollen root crowns and root suckers after damage to their trunks. Trees and shrubs act as nurse plants, moderating environmental conditions and offering seedlings and saplings protection. Shrubs are shade tolerant (Nixon and Muller 1997). <br/>
<br/>
One of the most distinctive western oaks, <i>Q. sadleriana </i>has a strong similarity to certain eastern North American and Asian species, suggesting its relict status (Nixon 2002). It hybridizes occasionally with <i>Q. garryana </i>var <i>. fruticosa</i>. The species grows as scattered shrubs in forests or as the dominant shrub in stands of montane chaparral. Self-perpetuating stands are unusual; most establish after fire from sprouting understory plants or after logging, and they are transitional to various forest types. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
